                      **  Welcome to LinCity Multiplayer  **

This is LinCity 1.14.0 — a multiplayer fork of the classic city simulation
game. The original LinCity did not include multiplayer support; this has been
added by ANerdyNub.

Based on lincity 1.13 (development version).


WHAT IS LINCITY
===============

Lincity is a city/country simulation game for Linux (SVGALIB and X), 
Solaris, FreeBSD, HPUX, AIX, SCO, IRIX, Compaq Tru64, BeOS, OS/2, VMS,
OS X, AtheOS, and Win32.

You are required to build and maintain a city. You must feed, house, 
provide jobs and goods for your residents. You can build a sustainable
economy with the help of renewable energy and recycling, or you can go for
broke and build rockets to escape from a pollution ridden and resource
starved planet, it's up to you.


WHAT'S NEW IN 1.14.0 (Multiplayer Fork)
========================================

This fork adds multiplayer support to Lincity — something the original
game never had. Key additions:

  * Network play over TCP/IP (client/server)
  * Synchronized yearly stats across all clients
  * Fixed network screen building placement (click-through bug)
  * Fixed save/load dialogs on Windows (MinGW)
  * Source code reorganized under src/ directory
  * Cross-compilation support for Windows (MinGW-w64)
  * Modern autotools build system

Upstream: https://github.com/ANerdyNub/lincity-multiplayer
Original: http://lincity.sourceforge.net


REQUIREMENTS
============

   *  SVGALIB 1.3.0 (or greater) OR X11 OR a Win32 OS.
   *  The libpng and libz libraries.
   *  A graphics card supported by your above choice.
   *  You probably need at least a 486DX2-66.
   *  You probably need at least 8 MB memory (16 MB for X or win32).


INSTALLATION (UNIX)
===================

To build from source:

      git clone https://github.com/ANerdyNub/lincity-multiplayer
      cd lincity-multiplayer
      ./configure
      make

Lincity will run out of the source directory.  To install:

      make install

To install to a custom directory:

      ./configure --prefix=/usr/mylocal


INSTALLATION (WIN32)
====================

Download the latest release from the GitHub page above, unzip, and
double-click lincity.exe.


UNINSTALLING (UNIX)
===================

If you still have the configured source directory:

      make uninstall

Otherwise (assuming you installed to /usr/local):

      rm /usr/local/bin/lincity
      rm /usr/local/bin/xlincity
      rm /usr/local/man/man6/lincity.6
      rm -rf /usr/local/share/lincity
      rm -rf $HOME/.lincity
      rm $HOME/.lincityrc


UNINSTALLING (WIN32)
====================

Simply delete the lincity directory to uninstall.


RUNNING LINCITY (UNIX)
======================

Usually you will invoke the game with 'lincity' or 'xlincity'.  
Typing 'lincity' will run the SVGA version, while typing 'xlincity' will
run the X Windows version.  The SVGA version will not run under X.

             lincity  [opts]
             xlincity [opts]

The following options apply to both.

        -w   Do some *crude* gamma correction to boost the red and blue.
        -R <num>
        -G <num>
        -B <num>
             These options allow you to boost the individual colours.
             <num> is a number between 0.0 and 1.0
             The default values for -w are  1.0   0.0   0.4

This option only applies to lincity:

        -m <num>
            Set the VGA mode (10=640x480, 11=800x600, 12=1024x768,
            13=1280x1024).

This option only applies to xlincity:

        -r   Add an extra border around the game.
        -d   Double the size of the window to 1280x960.


RUNNING LINCITY (WIN32)
=======================

Double click the LINCITY.EXE icon.


RUNNING LINCITY (CLIENT/SERVER)
===============================

LinCity Multiplayer supports network play over TCP/IP.  Start a server:

      xlincity --serve

Connect a client:

      xlincity --connect <server-address>

See --help for full options.


THE LINCITY HOME DIRECTORY
==========================

If you get a message such as "Error. Can't find LINCITY_HOME", this
means that lincity can't find its home directory.  To find its 
home directory, lincity searches for the file "colour.pal" in 
the following directories (in order):

        The directory pointed to by the $LINCITY_HOME environment variable
        The current working directory
        The default directory


LINCITY CONFIGURATION FILE
==========================

Lincity has a configuration file for saving defaults:

UNIX:       $HOME/.lincityrc
WINDOWS:    %LINCITY_HOME%\lincity.ini

To reset to defaults, simply delete the file.


LINCITY ARTWORK
===============

Starting with version 1.13, you can customize the lincity buildings
and animations by editing the icon image file at opening/icons.png
with your favorite image editor.  The palette is defined in colour.pal.


NOTES FOR SVGALIB VERSION
=========================

Higher resolutions are supported via the -m flag (see above).

As of version 1.12, lincity uses the mouse settings in your
SVGA configuration file (e.g. /etc/vga/vga.config).


NOTES FOR X VERSION
===================

When playing in 256 colour (8bpp) display modes, moving the mouse
outside the window may cause palette flashing.  An extra border is
added by default; you can disable it with -b.

There is a button that confines the mouse pointer within the X window.


NOTES FOR WIN32 VERSION
=======================

Lincity for Win32 automatically chooses border and pix doubling based
on your resolution:

       Resolution      Window Style     Border         Pix Doubling
       ------------    ------------    ------------    ------------
       640 x 480       Full screen     None            No
       800 x 600       Window          Yes             No
       1024 x 768      Window          Yes             No
       1152 x 864      Window          Yes             No
       1280 x 1024     Window          None            Yes

Save files are gzip compatible with the UNIX version of lincity.


INTERNATIONALIZATION
====================

Lincity supports translations via gettext.  To make a translation:

  1. Add your language code to po/LINGUAS
  2. Run `msginit -l <code>` in the po/ directory
  3. Edit the resulting .po file with your translations
  4. Run `make` in the po/ directory

Set the LANG environment variable before running lincity to use
your translation.


COMPILATION UNDER WIN32
=======================

Cross-compile using MinGW-w64:

      make -f Makefile.win          # release (no console)
      make -f Makefile.win.con      # debug (with console)


BUGS
====

Report bugs at: https://github.com/ANerdyNub/lincity-multiplayer/issues

Also see the file TODO.


HISTORY
=======

Ian Peters started writing lincity in June 1995 as an exercise in 
mouse control in SVGALIB. It quickly became a usable, then even fun, 
game to play. Over the next 18+ months it evolved into a challenging 
and stable game which, in a number of people's opinion, is worth uploading 
to the net.

In late 1997, lincity developers made grand plans for lincity version 2, 
an intergalactic space simulation with all the trimmings.  But from 
1998-1999, lincity underwent a period of hibernation, with only minor 
patches being applied.  

Development was restarted in late 1999 by Greg Sharp to provide
some moderate improvements, including networking support, GUI
improvements and additional gameplay developments.  Networking 
support was subsequently dropped in 2001.

In mid-2001, Greg was joined by Corey Keasling, who helped to bring
the game to sourceforge.net.  In late 2001, Corey became
co-maintainer.  Version 1.12 was released in December 2003.

In 2026, ANerdyNub forked the game to add multiplayer support,
creating version 1.14.0. The fork includes networking, bugfixes,
build system modernization, and cross-platform improvements.


